-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - Dec 31
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Tue Dec 30, 2014 09:07PM EST
-- None



HONG KONG, Dec 31 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Wednesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  -- Hong Kong's government will kill all the 15,000 live poultry in a wholesale market in Cheung Sha Wan and close the market for 21 days after samples of chicken imported from mainland China tested positive for the H7N9 bird flu virus, the government announced early on Wednesday. (http://bit.ly/13I8d1h) -- About 10 investors from around the world voiced "immense interest" in acquiring the heavily indebted broadcaster ATV in Hong Kong but nothing came to pass, executive director Ip Ka-po said as the TV station teetered on the brink of collapse. (http://bit.ly/1zuI3Z2)  THE STANDARD -- Three companies open their retail books on Wednesday in separate initial public offerings that can raise up to a combined HK$1.26 billion ($162.5 million), including taxis and public light buses insurer Target Insurance (Holdings), which aims to raise up to HK$225 million. (http://bit.ly/1wzqEfA) -- Vineyards have been the latest popular investment of Asian investors with more Hong Kong people purchasing them,  global real estate consultancy Knight Frank said in a report. (http://bit.ly/1BhbVdI)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- Former executive director of Sun Hung Kai Properties <0016.HK> Thomas Chan officially lodged an appeal against his convictions for conspiracy to commit misconduct in public office and conspiracy to offer an advantage to a public servant that had landed him a six-year jail term.